<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-971-922  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 971 922.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Design  Nov 1989 v21 n9 p584(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automating physical system modelling using bond graphs.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hood, S.J.; Palmer, E.R.; Withers, D.H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A designer can use a mathematical model of a physical system tostudy its dynamic performance.andP;  The goal of the Design Analysisfor Reliability Tool (DART) project at the IBM Thomas J WatsonResearch Center was to automate some of the steps of buildingmathematical models.andP;  The bond-graph method was used to representa physical system as a lumped parameter model.andP;  The DART programaccepts a bond graph entered through a graphic editor.andP;  Stateequations are automatically derived from the bond graph.andP;  Specificconstitutive laws for the general relationships represented by thebond-graph nodes are entered through a full-screen editor.andP;  Theequations are solved using the Dynamic Simulation Language (DSL).andO;(Reprinted by permission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Mathematical ModelsParametersSimulation LanguagesModelingTheoretical ResearchGraph TheoryMechanical EngineeringComputer-Aided EngineeringPrototype.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Comparison of methods. (chart)Bond-graph graphic editor. (chart)DSL graphic output. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>